# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: coach-baseball
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:coach-baseball/1909-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1909 throughout the world.
[src:coach-baseball/1950-in-baseball-p01] The following are the baseball events of the year 1950 throughout the world.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] The **2015 World Series** was the championship series of Major League Baseball's (MLB) 2015 season.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] The 111th edition of the World Series, it was a best-of-seven playoff between the National League (NL) champion New York Mets and the American League (AL) champion Kansas City Royals.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] The series was played between October 27 and November 1, with the Royals winning the series 4 games to 1, clinching the team's second World Series and first since the 1985 series.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] It was the first time since 2010 that the Series extended into November.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] The Royals had home field advantage for the series because of the AL's 6–3 victory in the Major League Baseball All-Star Game.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] It was the 13th World Series in which home field advantage was awarded to the league that won the All-Star Game, a practice that was discontinued after the 2016 season.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] The series was played in a 2-3-2 format: the Royals hosted Games 1 and 2, and would have hosted Games 6 and 7 had they been needed.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] The Royals became the first team since the Oakland Athletics in the 1989 World Series to win the World Series after losing in the previous year; and in addition, they became the first expansion team to win the World Series since the Florida Marlins won it all in 2003.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] It was also the first World Series played between two expansion teams.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] Salvador Pérez was named the World Series Most Valuable Player.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] The 2015 World Series is considered to be above average in most rankings.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] This was the first World Series in which both teams were expansion teams, which are teams that were formed after the 1960 season; the Mets began play in 1962 and the Royals in 1969.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] With five and four pennants respectively, the Mets and Royals have the most league championships among the expansion franchises.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] Each team was also seeking to end a championship drought; the Royals' previous championship was in 1985, with the Mets' last title coming one year later in 1986.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] The Mets made their fifth appearance in the World Series after sweeping the Cubs 4–0 in the 2015 National League Championship Series (NLCS).
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] The Mets qualified for the postseason by winning the National League (NL) East, their sixth division title.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] The third-seeded Mets faced the #2 seed Los Angeles Dodgers in the 2015 NL Division Series, winning in five games.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] In the 2015 NLCS, Daniel Murphy led the team by hitting home runs in each game of the four-game sweep of the fifth-seeded Chicago Cubs.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] By winning the NLCS, the Mets became the first expansion franchise to play in the World Series five times.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] In addition, the Mets have made World Series appearances in all but one of their six decades of existence, not appearing in any that were played during the 1990s.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] This was the first World Series appearance for Mets' manager Terry Collins, who had never reached the postseason as a manager prior to 2015.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] The Royals made their second consecutive appearance in the World Series, both under Ned Yost, and fourth overall.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] They won the 1985 World Series against the St.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] Louis Cardinals, and lost their two other appearances, the 1980 World Series against the Philadelphia Phillies and the 2014 World Series against the San Francisco Giants.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] The Royals qualified for the postseason by winning the American League (AL) Central, their seventh division title and their first since winning the AL West in 1985.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] The top-seeded Royals faced the #5 seed Houston Astros in the 2015 American League Division Series, winning in five games.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] They followed that up in the 2015 American League Championship Series, beating the second-seeded Toronto Blue Jays in six games.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] By winning the ALCS, the Royals became the first team to play in consecutive World Series since the Texas Rangers played in the 2010 World Series and 2011 World Series.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] The American League won the 2015 All-Star Game, therefore the Royals had home field advantage for the series.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] The Mets and the Royals hadn't played each other since 2013.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] Though the Mets boasted four starting pitchers who could throw over 95 miles per hour (153 km/h)—Matt Harvey, Noah Syndergaard, Jacob deGrom, and Steven Matz—the Royals had the best team batting average against pitches over that speed during the 2015 season.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] And while the Mets' starting pitchers had the best strikeout-to-walk ratio in MLB, the Royals' roster of strong contact hitters led baseball in contact rate.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] The Royals also had a superior defensive team, finishing second in the majors in Defensive Runs Saved, while the Mets finished 21st.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] The Royals bullpen, anchored by Wade Davis and Kelvin Herrera, also provided a strength.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] While the Mets hitters performed better against left-handed pitchers than right-handed pitchers, the Royals four starting pitchers, Johnny Cueto, Edinson Vólquez, Yordano Ventura, and Chris Young, and primary relievers, Davis, Herrera, Ryan Madson, and Luke Hochevar, were right-handed.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] The ceremonial first pitch was thrown out by George Brett while Andy Grammer sang the national anthem.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] Matt Harvey started Game 1 for the Mets, while Edinson Vólquez started for the Royals.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] Vólquez's father had died earlier in the day.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] He was not aware of his father's death until after he left the game.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] On the first pitch thrown by Harvey, Alcides Escobar hit an inside-the-park home run, the first in a World Series game since Mule Haas in Game 4 of the 1929 World Series, and the first hit by a leadoff batter since Patsy Dougherty did it in Game 2 of the 1903 World Series.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] In the fourth inning, Murphy recorded the Mets' first hit, and later scored their first run on a hit by Travis d'Arnaud.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] Curtis Granderson hit a home run in the fifth inning to give the Mets a 2–1 lead.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] The Mets took a 3–1 lead in the top of the sixth when Michael Conforto drove in Yoenis Céspedes with a sacrifice fly.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] Mike Moustakas then saved a run with a diving stop and throw out to first to end the top of the sixth.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] Eric Hosmer reduced the lead to 3–2 with a sacrifice fly, and set a new Royals' postseason run batted in (RBI) record in the process.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] A single by Moustakas tied the game at three, but in the top of the eighth, Wilmer Flores reached on an fielding error by Hosmer, allowing Juan Lagares to score the go-ahead run and give the Mets a 4–3 lead.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] In the bottom of the ninth with the Mets two outs away from taking Game 1, Alex Gordon tied the game for the Royals with a home run to deep center field, as Jeurys Familia blew his first save in six postseason opportunities and his first since July 30.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] With the home run, Gordon became the first player since Scott Brosius in the 2001 World Series, and just the fifth player in history, to tie a World Series game on a home run in the ninth inning.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] In the bottom of the 11th inning, Granderson robbed the speedy Jarrod Dyson of a multi-base hit with a running, leaping catch that prevented what probably would have been a lead-off triple.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] The Mets went on to get out of the inning.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] In the bottom of the 14th, Escobar reached first on a throwing error by David Wright, and Bartolo Colón gave up a base hit to Ben Zobrist, allowing Escobar to reach third.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] Hosmer hit a sacrifice fly to Granderson in right field to drive in the winning run.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] This was the first time in World Series history that the same player scored both the first run of the game on the first pitch, and the last run of the game on the final pitch.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] CDT, lasting five hours and nine minutes.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] The game tied the record for the longest game by innings in World Series history, shared with Game 2 in the 1916 World Series and Game 3 in the 2005 World Series.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] However, the record has since been surpassed by Games 3 of the 2018 and 2025 World Series, each of which was 18 innings long.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] The loss made Colón the oldest player ever to lose a World Series game.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] With the loss, the Mets fell to 0–5 in Game 1 of the World Series, having lost the first game in all 5 of their appearances, including the two years they won the series (1969 and 1986).
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] In Game 2, Jacob deGrom started for the Mets, and Johnny Cueto started for the Royals.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] The ceremonial first pitch was thrown out by Medal of Honor recipients Don Ballard, Charles Hagemeister, and Roger Donlon while country singer and Missouri native Sara Evans sang the national anthem.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] Cueto walked Curtis Granderson to lead off the fourth and Daniel Murphy one out later.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] Yoenis Céspedes's hit into a forceout at second before Lucas Duda's RBI single put the Mets up 1–0.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] Duda produced the Mets' only other hit in the game in the second and Cueto retired them in order through the ninth.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] In the fifth inning, deGrom allowed a leadoff walk to Alex Gordon and subsequent single to Alex Rios before Alcides Escobar's RBI single tied the game.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] Ben Zobrist's groundout moved the runners up and after Lorenzo Cain lined out to center, Eric Hosmer's two-run single put the Royals up 3–1.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] Kendrys Morales's single moved Hosmer to third and Mike Moustakas's single made it 4-1 Royals.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] The Royals blew the game open in the eighth off of Jon Niese, who allowed a leadoff single to Moustakas, subsequent single to Salvador Pérez, and RBI double to Gordon.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] Addison Reed relieved Niese and allowed a sacrifice fly to Paulo Orlando and RBI triple to Escobar to make it 7-1 Kansas City.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] Cueto became the first AL pitcher since Jim Lonborg in the 1967 World Series to throw a World Series complete game while allowing two hits or fewer.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] The series shifted to Citi Field, the home stadium of the Mets, for Game 3.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] Yordano Ventura started for the Royals and Noah Syndergaard started for the Mets.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] The ceremonial first pitch was thrown by Mike Piazza to catcher Kevin Plawecki while New York native Billy Joel sang the national anthem.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] With no designated hitter (DH) in NL parks, the Mets started Michael Conforto, their DH for Game 2, in the outfield instead of Juan Lagares, and the Royals did not start Kendrys Morales, their regular DH.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] Zobrist scored for the Royals in the first inning on a force play.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] In the bottom of the first inning, Wright hit a two-run homer that also scored Granderson.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] For the Royals, Alex Ríos drove Salvador Pérez home in the second inning, and scored on a passed ball by d'Arnaud, giving the Royals a 3–2 lead.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] After a Syndergaard single, Granderson hit a two-run home run just over the right field wall in the third inning, and the Mets took a 4–3 lead.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] The Mets added a run in the fourth inning on an RBI single by Conforto, and four more in the sixth inning, including an RBI single by Juan Uribe, in his first at bat since September 20.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] In the fifth inning, Royals player Raúl A.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] Mondesí made his Major League Baseball debut, pinch hitting for Danny Duffy.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] Mondesí became the first player ever to make his MLB debut in the World Series.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] The ceremonial first pitch was thrown out by country singer Tim McGraw, son of former Mets relief pitcher Tug McGraw while Demi Lovato sang the national anthem.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] The starting pitchers for Game 4 were Chris Young of the Royals and Steven Matz of the Mets.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] Conforto scored the game's first run with a home run in the third inning, and Flores scored later in the inning on a Granderson sacrifice fly, when right-fielder Ríos did not make an immediate throw home (thinking his catch was the third out of the inning).
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] The Royals cut the deficit to 2–1 in the top of the fifth when Pérez doubled and was then driven in by Gordon.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] However, in the bottom of the fifth, Conforto hit another home run, becoming the first rookie to hit two home runs in a World Series game since Andruw Jones in 1996.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] In the sixth inning, Zobrist hit his eighth double of the postseason, tying a postseason record previously set by Albert Pujols and David Freese of the 2011 St.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] Lorenzo Cain drove in Zobrist in to make it a 3–2 game.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] In the eighth inning, after recording the first out, Tyler Clippard walked two consecutive batters to force Terry Collins to bring in Familia.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] A key fielding error by Daniel Murphy allowed the tying run to score.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] The Royals took the lead on an RBI single from Moustakas, and then Pérez added an insurance run with another RBI base hit to give Kansas City the 5–3 lead.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] For Familia, it was his second blown save of the series, and second out of seven opportunities this postseason, though this one could be partly attributed to Murphy's error.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] Wade Davis converted a two-inning save for the Royals, his fourth overall this postseason.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] Davis pitched a perfect eighth, but got into some trouble with one out in the ninth when Murphy hit a hard grounder that Moustakas could not field cleanly, and then Céspedes got a base hit to bring the winning run to the plate in Duda.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] However, Duda hit a soft line drive that was caught by Moustakas, who then doubled off Céspedes at first to end the game.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] Céspedes had started running thinking the ball would hit the ground.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] scored the tying run in the top of the ninth inning.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] throwing the last pitch of the 2015 World Series.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] Vólquez returned to the Dominican Republic for his father's funeral the day after Game 1, but he returned in time to start Game 5.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] New York City Fire Department firefighter Frank Pizarro sang the national anthem, New York native Tony Bennett performed "America the Beautiful", and the first pitches were thrown by Cleon Jones, Mookie Wilson, and Darryl Strawberry.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] Granderson led off the first inning with a home run for the Mets, and scored the Mets' second run in the sixth inning.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] The Mets had a chance to break the game open in that sixth inning as they loaded the bases with no outs, but had to settle for one run after Céspedes lined a foul ball off his leg and was injured, leaving the game after popping up for the first out of the inning.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] Duda hit a sacrifice fly before d'Arnaud grounded out to end the inning.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] Harvey pitched eight shutout innings for the Mets, and convinced Collins to keep him in the game for the ninth.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] He then gave up a leadoff walk to Cain in the ninth inning, and the Royals got a run when Hosmer drove Cain in with a double, prompting Collins to call upon Familia to relieve Harvey.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] After a groundout by Moustakas advanced Hosmer to third base with one out, Pérez hit a ground ball to third baseman David Wright.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] Wright, after checking Hosmer at third, threw to first base for the second out; however, Hosmer broke for home as soon as the ball was thrown.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] Duda, who fielded the out at first, threw wide at home attempting to throw Hosmer out, and the latter scored the tying run.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] This resulted in Familia blowing his third save of the postseason and the series; his eight save opportunities tied the postseason record set in 2002 by Robb Nen.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] In the top of the 12th inning, with Addison Reed pitching for the Mets, Pérez hit a single for the Royals.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] Pinch running for Pérez, Dyson stole a base and scored on a single by pinch hitter Christian Colón.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] The Royals loaded the bases, and Cain drove home three more runs with a double off of Bartolo Colón.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] Davis pitched a shutout inning for the Royals to complete the series and win the championship.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] With Game 5 having crept well past midnight eastern time, Flores struck out looking to end the game, series, and baseball season, with the Royals winning and ending their 30-year World Series title drought.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] Pérez, who batted 8-for-22 (.364) in the series, and caught every inning for the Royals with the exception of the final inning of the series, won the World Series Most Valuable Player Award.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] He became the first catcher to win the award since Pat Borders won it in the 1992 World Series, and the second Venezuelan player, following Pablo Sandoval, who won it in the 2012 World Series.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] Paulo Orlando made history as the first Brazilian player to win the World Series and the third South American to do so, the first was the Venezuelan player Luis Aparicio and the second was the Colombian player Edgar Rentería.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] Fox broadcast the series in the United States, with play-by-play announcer Joe Buck calling the action along with color analysts Harold Reynolds and Tom Verducci and field reporters Ken Rosenthal and Erin Andrews.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] The pregame and postgame show featured host Kevin Burkhardt with analysts Frank Thomas, Raul Ibanez, Pete Rose, and Alex Rodriguez.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] Fox Deportes offered a Spanish telecast of the series in the United States.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] The MLB International feed featured Matt Vasgersian and John Smoltz with play-by-play and analysis, respectively.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] Fox suffered an outage during their broadcast of Game 1.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] Fox temporarily switched to the MLB International feed of the game with Vasgersian and Smoltz to restore coverage.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] The video from the feed was then accompanied by Fox's commentators before the full Fox production was restored.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] The World Series started on a Tuesday for the second straight year, instead of a Wednesday as in the past.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] Had the World Series gone to a Game 6, it would have competed against Election Day coverage for the first time in World Series history, though 2015 was not a presidential or midterm election.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] All World Series held since 2015 were scheduled to complete prior to Election Day.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] Game 1 of the World Series averaged a 4.6 rating on Fox, making it the most watched Game 1 since the 2010 World Series.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] Game 2 then had a 3.9 rating, up 24 percent from last season's Game 2.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] The series also recorded the most watched Game 3 since 2009.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] Game 5 went head-to-head with an *NBC Sunday Night Football* game between the Green Bay Packers and the Denver Broncos (both undefeated).
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] Media sources like *Sporting News* predicted this heavy competition would result in series-low ratings.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] While the football game drew the larger audience, the Royals and Mets did average a 10.0 rating, the highest for a World Series Game 5 since 2003.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] ESPN Radio aired the series, with Dan Shulman on play-by-play, Aaron Boone handling color commentary, and Buster Olney serving as field reporter.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] Tampa Bay Rays pitcher Chris Archer served as a guest commentator for selected innings in Games 1, 2 and 5.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] Marc Kestecher anchored pre-game and post-game coverage for the network along with Chris Singleton and Peter Pascarelli.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] Locally, the series was broadcast on the teams' flagship radio stations with their respective announcing crews.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] In New York, WOR aired the games in English, with Howie Rose and Josh Lewin announcing, while WEPN-AM aired the games in Spanish, with Juan Alicea and Max Pérez Jiménez announcing.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] In Kansas City, KCSP broadcast the games, with Denny Matthews, Ryan Lefebvre, Steve Stewart, and Steve Physioc announcing.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] WEPN-FM and WHB, the ESPN Radio affiliates in New York and Kansas City respectively, aired the network's coverage of the series in those cities.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] Johnny Cueto's Game 2 pitching gem was the most recent World Series complete game until Yoshinobu Yamamoto’s Game 2 complete game in the 2025 World Series, nearly a full 10 years to the date of Cueto’s, on October 25, 2025.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] The Royals became the first team and in World Series history to start three pitchers—Yordano Ventura, Edinson Volquez, and Cueto—born outside the United States.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] Later, the Astros would accomplish this feat when they started four foreign-born pitchers in the 2021 World Series.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] The Mets and Royals met on Opening Day of the 2016 season, on April 3, 2016, for a Sunday Night Baseball game in Kansas City.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] It was the first ever time in MLB history a defending champion opened against the team they beat in the World Series.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] The Mets and Royals split the short two-game series to start the season, while the Mets would sweep the other half of their four games season series at Citi Field in June.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] As was the case with their 1985 championship, the Royals missed the postseason a year after winning the World Series.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] After 81 and 80-win seasons for the next two years, a pair of 100-loss seasons followed in 2018 and 2019, during which management dismantled the core of the 2015 team and Ned Yost retired from managing.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] Of the players who played for the 2015 Royals, only Salvador Pérez remained with the team as of 2026.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] The Mets qualified for the 2016 National League Wild Card Game after an 87-win season, but lost to the San Francisco Giants.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] This was followed by a 70-win season in Terry Collins' final year as manager.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] Both teams would next win a postseason series a day apart in 2024 when both won their respective Wild Card Series match-ups (against Baltimore and Milwaukee, respectively) to advance to the Division Series.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] This was the only World Series appearance by a New York City team during the 2010s decade.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] The 2010s became the first decade since the 1910s that a team from New York City failed to win a World Series.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] In the 1989 film *Back to the Future Part II*, the Chicago Cubs are depicted as the 2015 World Series champions, defeating a fictional American League team from Miami, whose mascot is an alligator, in a five-game sweep ending on or before October 21.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] He also explained that the October 21 prediction was based on the postseason structure at the time of writing (prior to Division Series or Wild Card Series), and thus could have been accurate.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] In the actual 2015 postseason, the Cubs advanced to the National League Championship Series (NLCS), but were swept in four games by the New York Mets.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] The final game of that series took place on October 21, the same date as the fictional events in the film.
[src:coach-baseball/2015-world-series] One year later, however, the Cubs did win the World Series, beating the Cleveland Indians in seven games.
[src:coach-baseball/ace-baseball] In baseball, an **ace** is a starting pitcher considered the best pitcher on a team's starting rotation.
[src:coach-baseball/ace-baseball] Barring injury or exceptional circumstances, a team's ace typically starts on Opening Day.
[src:coach-baseball/ace-baseball] In addition, aces are usually preferred to start crucial playoff games, sometimes on three days' rest.
[src:coach-baseball/ace-baseball] The term may be a derivation of the nickname of Asa Brainard (real first name: "Asahel"), a 19th-century star pitcher, who was sometimes referred to as "Ace".
[src:coach-baseball/ace-baseball] In the early days of baseball, the term *ace* was used to refer to a run.
[src:coach-baseball/ace-baseball] Modern baseball analysts and fans have started using the term *ace* to refer to the elite pitchers in the game, not necessarily to the best starting pitcher on each team.
[src:coach-baseball/ace-baseball] For example, the April 27, 1981, *Sports Illustrated* cover was captioned "The Amazing A's and Their Five Aces" to describe the starting rotation of the 1981 Oakland Athletics, which featured Mike Norris, Rick Langford, Matt Keough, Steve McCatty, and Brian Kingman.
[src:coach-baseball/al-pedrique] Pedrique served as the Houston Astros bench coach and as manager of the Arizona Diamondbacks.
[src:coach-baseball/al-pedrique] He also served as the first base coach of the Oakland Athletics a season before being shuffled to third base coaching for two further seasons.
[src:coach-baseball/al-pedrique] He is currently the manager for the Double-A Reading Fightin Phils.
[src:coach-baseball/al-pedrique] Pedrique was signed by the New York Mets in 1978 and made his MLB debut nine years later.
[src:coach-baseball/al-pedrique] After five games with the 1987 Mets team he was traded to the Pittsburgh Pirates where he hit .301 in his rookie season but only managed a .188 cumulative batting average after that.
[src:coach-baseball/al-pedrique] Pedrique was a career .247 hitter with one home run, 36 runs batted in (RBI), 32 runs, 18 doubles, one triple, and five stolen bases in 174 games.
[src:coach-baseball/al-pedrique] After retiring, Pedrique managed in the minors for the Arizona Diamondbacks, Houston Astros, and Kansas City Royals organizations from 2000 to 2002.
[src:coach-baseball/al-pedrique] He came back to the majors in 2003 as a third base coach for the Diamondbacks.
[src:coach-baseball/al-pedrique] In 2004, Pedrique began the season as manager of the Tucson Sidewinders, the Diamondbacks Triple-A affiliate, but was hired as manager of the Diamondbacks on an interim basis when Bob Brenly was fired in July.
[src:coach-baseball/al-pedrique] He was replaced by Wally Backman, and then Bob Melvin, at the end of the season.
[src:coach-baseball/al-pedrique] While serving as a special assistant for the Houston Astros in 2007, Pedrique was in Venezuela and championed a 16-year old Jose Altuve to the front office, convincing them that he had the talent and strength to eventually play in the major leagues.
[src:coach-baseball/al-pedrique] Altuve had been dismissed by scouts as being too short and thought he was lying about his age.
[src:coach-baseball/al-pedrique] The Astros hired Pedrique as their bench coach on October 31, 2009, after previously serving as their Minor League Field Coordinator and third base coach.
[src:coach-baseball/al-pedrique] In 2013, he was hired as manager of the Yankees' Single-A affiliate Charleston RiverDogs.
[src:coach-baseball/al-pedrique] In 2014, the New York Yankees promoted Pedrique to the manager of the Tampa Yankees.
[src:coach-baseball/al-pedrique] In 2015, he was promoted to manager of the Trenton Thunder.
[src:coach-baseball/al-pedrique] On January 6, 2016, Pedrique was announced as the manager of the Scranton/Wilkes-Barre RailRiders.
[src:coach-baseball/al-pedrique] In his first season as manager, he led the RailRiders to a North Division title.
[src:coach-baseball/al-pedrique] Pedrique then led the RailRiders to the International League's Governors' Cup championship and won.
[src:coach-baseball/al-pedrique] After that, he then led the RailRiders to win Triple-A National Championship Game and won that as well.
[src:coach-baseball/al-pedrique] In his second and final season as RailRiders manager, Pedrique led the RailRiders to a North Division title once again.
[src:coach-baseball/al-pedrique] The RailRiders ended up losing to the Durham Bulls, who went on to win the Triple A National Championship at the RailRiders PNC Field, in the Governors' Cup Championship.
[src:coach-baseball/al-pedrique] On December 4, 2017, Pedrique was hired by the Oakland A's as first base coach.
[src:coach-baseball/al-pedrique] He then shifted to third base after one season.
[src:coach-baseball/al-pedrique] On March 29, 2021, he was named as the new manager for the Jacksonville Jumbo Shrimp, the Triple-A affiliate for the Miami Marlins.
[src:coach-baseball/al-pedrique] On November 17, 2021, the Marlins hired Pedrique as their third base and infield coach for the 2022 season.
[src:coach-baseball/al-pedrique] Pedrique was named manager of the Double-A Reading Fightin Phils for the 2023 season.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The **Arizona Diamondbacks** (often referred to as the **D-backs**) are an American professional baseball team based in Phoenix, Arizona.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The Diamondbacks compete in Major League Baseball (MLB) as a member club of the National League (NL) West Division.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The franchise was established on March 9, 1995 and began play in 1998 as an expansion team.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The team plays its home games at Chase Field.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] Along with the Tampa Bay Rays, the Diamondbacks are one of the newest teams in MLB and are the youngest team to win a World Series, doing so in only their fourth season of existence in 2001.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] After a fifth-place finish in their inaugural season, the Diamondbacks made several off-season acquisitions, including future Hall of Fame pitcher Randy Johnson, who won four consecutive Cy Young Awards in his first four seasons with the team.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] In 1999, Arizona won 100 games and their first division championship.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] In 2001, they won the World Series over the three-time defending champion New York Yankees, becoming the fastest expansion team in MLB history to win the World Series and the first and only men's major professional sports team in Arizona to win a championship.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] 22 years later they won their second NLCS and returned to the World Series, losing to the Texas Rangers.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] On March 9, 1995, Phoenix was awarded an expansion franchise to begin play for the 1998 season.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] A $130 million franchise fee was paid to Major League Baseball (MLB).
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] On January 16, 1997, owners of existing MLB teams voted to put the Diamondbacks in the National League.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The Diamondbacks' first major league game was played against the Colorado Rockies on March 31, 1998, at Bank One Ballpark.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The ballpark was renamed Chase Field in 2005, as a result of Bank One's merger with JPMorgan Chase.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] Since their debut, the Diamondbacks have won two Wild Card Series, five NL West division titles, two NL pennants, and the 2001 World Series.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] They were the fastest expansion franchise in baseball history to win a World Series after defeating the Yankees in Game 7 during the 2001 postseason.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] After beating the Philadelphia Phillies 4–2 in Game 7 of the 2023 NLCS at Citizens Bank Park in Philadelphia, the Diamondbacks returned to the World Series for the first time since 2001 – against the Texas Rangers on October 27, 2023.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] They lost the series 4–1, with the clinching Game 5 loss at home in Arizona on November 1, 2023.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The Diamondbacks' original colors were purple, black, teal, and copper.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] Their logo was an italicized block letter "A" with a diamond pattern, with the crossbar represented by a snake's tongue.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] This period saw the Diamondbacks wear several uniform combinations.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] At home, the Diamondbacks wore cream uniforms with purple pinstripes.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The primary sleeved uniform, worn from 1998 to 2000, featured the full team name ("Diamond" and "Backs" stacked together) in front and chest numbers.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The alternate sleeveless version contained the "A" logo on the right chest and was paired with purple undershirts.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] Before the 2001 season, the sleeved uniform was changed to feature the "A" logo.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] In all three uniforms, player names were teal with purple trim, and numbers were purple with white with teal trim.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The Diamondbacks' primary road gray uniform also had purple pinstripes.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The first version featured "Arizona" in purple with white and teal trim along with black drop shadows, with chest numbers added.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] Player names were in purple with white trim, and numbers were teal with white and purple trim.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] In 2001, the uniform became sleeveless with black undershirts, and the lettering scheme was changed to purple with white, copper, and black accents.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The alternate home purple uniform featured "Arizona" in teal with white and copper trim and black drop shadows.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The letters were rendered in teal with copper and white trim, but were changed to copper with teal and white trim after only one season.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The alternate road black uniform featured the "A" logo on the right chest, while letters were purple with white trim and numbers were teal with white and purple trim.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] A zigzag pattern of teal, copper, and purple was featured on the sleeves.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] In 2001, the uniform was changed to feature "Arizona" in front.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The letters became purple with white and copper trim.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The Diamondbacks initially wore four different cap versions.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The primary home cap is all-purple, while the road cap is black with a teal brim.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] They also wore a cream cap with purple brim and a teal cap with purple brim.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] All designs featured the primary "A" logo.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] In 1999, the road cap became all-black and contained the alternate "D-snake" logo rendered in copper.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] Also, the teal and cream alternate caps were dropped.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The left sleeve of all four uniforms contained the snake logo with the full team name until the 2004 season, when it became exclusive to the road black uniform.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The franchise unveiled new uniforms and colors of Sedona red, Sonoran sand, and black on November 8, 2006.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The red shade is named for the sandstone canyon at Red Rock State Park near Sedona, while the beige (sand) shade is named for the Sonoran Desert.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] A sleeve patch was added featuring a lowercase "d" and "b" configured to look like a snake's head.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The team also kept the "D" logo, which was slightly altered and put on an all-red cap to be used as their game cap.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] They kept the "A" logo with the new colors applied to it, with a solid black cap used as the alternate cap.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] Arizona's updated color scheme bore a striking resemblance to the Houston Astros' color scheme (brick red, sand, and black) that the Astros used until 2012, as well as the NHL's Phoenix Coyotes, whose adoption of those colors predated the Diamondbacks by four years.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The white home uniform featured "D-Backs" in red with sand and black trim.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The road gray uniform featured "Arizona" in red with sand and black trim.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] Player names were red with black trim while numbers were black with red trim.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The alternate red uniform contained "D-Backs" in sand with red and black trim, with player names in sand with black trim and numbers in black with sand trim.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] There were two versions of the alternate black uniform.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] One design has the alternate "A" logo on the right chest, while the other has "Arizona" written in red with black and sand trim.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The latter was introduced in 2013 as a tribute to the victims of the Yarnell Hill Fire.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] On both uniforms, player names were sand with red trim and numbers in red with sand trim.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] (right) in the 2007–2015 red alternate uniform with road pants.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] Before the 2016 season, the Diamondbacks reincorporated teal into its color scheme while keeping Sedona Red, Sonoran Sand, and black.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] They also unveiled eight different uniform combinations, including two separate home white and away grey uniforms.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] One major difference between the two sets is that the non-teal uniforms feature a snakeskin pattern on the shoulders, while the teal-trimmed uniforms include a charcoal/grey snakeskin pattern on the back.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] Arizona also kept the throwback pinstriped sleeveless uniforms from their 2001 championship season for use during Thursday home games.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] Starting with the 2020 season, the Diamondbacks made slight redesigns to their uniforms.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The snakeskin patterns were removed while the teal-trimmed grey uniforms were retired.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The team also reverted to a standard grey uniform after wearing a darker shade on the previous set.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] Two home white uniforms remain in use: the primary Sedona Red and the alternate teal.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] They would also wear two black uniforms: one with the primary "A" logo on the left chest and the other with "Los D-Backs" trimmed in teal.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] Three cap designs were also unveiled, all with a black base: the primary "A" cap, the teal-trimmed "snake" cap (paired exclusively on the teal alternates), and the sand-trimmed "snake" cap with red brim (paired exclusively on the Sedona Red alternates).
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The Nike swoosh logo is also placed on the right chest near the shoulder.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] In 2022, the Diamondbacks introduced a red "A" cap with black brim.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] In 2021, the Diamondbacks were one of seven teams to wear Nike "City Connect" uniforms.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The design is primarily sand and has "Serpientes" in black script lettering emblazoned in front.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The first "S" in "Serpientes" was shaped to resemble a rattlesnake.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The right sleeve has the flag of Arizona patch recolored to the Diamondbacks' red, sand, and black scheme, and the left sleeve has the "A" logo recolored to black and sand.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The cap is primarily sand with black brim and has the "A" logo in black and sand; the regular batting helmet is used with the uniform.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] Initially, the Diamondbacks wore white pants with this uniform, but has since switched to sand pants.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] Before the 2023 season, the Diamondbacks promoted the alternate white uniform with teal accents to its primary home uniform and retired the previous Sedona Red white uniform.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] This is due to a new Nike rule that limits teams to four regular uniforms plus the "City Connect" uniform.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] Coming off their second World Series appearance in 2023, the Diamondbacks unveiled refreshed uniform designs starting in 2024.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] Turquoise returned full-time as an accent color on all uniforms along with Sedona red and black, but sand was removed except on the "City Connect" uniform.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The home uniform is now a cream base with black piping, featuring the "A" logo on the left chest.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The road grey uniform with black piping featured "Arizona" in Sedona red with teal and black outlines.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The alternate black uniform with teal piping shared the same features as the home uniform.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The alternate Sedona red uniform incorporated the full "Diamondbacks" wordmark in black with teal and Sedona red outlines, along with teal numbers trimmed in black on the left chest.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] All uniforms featured the snake head alternate logo on either sleeve, with the sponsor logo (Avnet since 2023) on the other sleeve.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The home cap is Sedona red with black brim and featured the "A" logo, and its all-black counterpart is worn with both the home and black alternate uniform.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The road cap is black with Sedona red trim and featured the return of the "D-snake" logo and is worn with both the road and alternate Sedona red uniform.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The all-Sedona red alternate cap shared the same features as the road cap and is worn with the Sedona red uniform.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] In 2025, the Diamondbacks released a second "City Connect" uniform, updating the "Serpientes" wordmark but recolored to the original purple and teal colors.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The uniforms take designs from all their different uniform combinations since they became a franchise in 1998.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The jersey pays tribute to the original jersey with the Heritage Pinstripes worn from 1998−2006 as well as its “evolutionary jersey” from 2016−2019 by blending pinstripes with a snakeskin pattern.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The jersey still features the word "Serpientes" with the "S" remaining the same from their previous version of their city connect, with the rest being a new design.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The faux sleeves pay tribute to the 2001 World Series-winning team, which featured sleeveless jerseys that had a different colored sleeve.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The sleeves also feature the Flag of Arizona on one sleeve, the state outline with a baseball silhouette and the year 1998, the founding year of the club, plus features a light color of teal in the shape of 48, as Arizona is the 48th state in the union.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The trim on the sleeve is in teal and was used on the team uniform from 1998−2006, which is in the shape of a Diamondback Rattlesnake skin.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The collar features the phrase "Arizona Born", pays tribute to the team's home state.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The cap is in the original purple and has a teal brim that features the "S" Serpientes logo.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] On July 18, 2023, a federal bankruptcy court granted Bally Sports' parent company Diamond Sports Group a motion to decline its contract with the Diamondbacks as part of its chapter 11 bankruptcy.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] As a result, Major League Baseball's local media division assumed production of the Diamondbacks' regional telecasts (maintaining staff such as commentators) and distributed them via local television providers and MLB.tv.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] As of 2024, these games are branded as **DBacks.TV**.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The primary television play-by-play voice for the team's first nine seasons of play was Thom Brennaman, who also broadcast baseball and college football games nationally for Fox Television.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] Brennaman was the TV announcer for the Chicago Cubs and Cincinnati Reds (along with his father Marty Brennaman) before being hired by Diamondbacks founder Jerry Colangelo in 1996, two years before the team would begin play.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] In October 2006, Brennaman left the Diamondbacks to call games with his father for the Reds beginning in 2007, signing a four-year deal.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] On November 1, 2006, the team announced that the TV voice of the Milwaukee Brewers since 2002, Daron Sutton, would be hired as the Diamondbacks primary TV play-by-play voice.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] Sutton signed a five-year contract with a team option for three more years.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] Sutton's signature chants included "let's get some runs" when the D-backs trail in late innings.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] Former Diamondbacks and Cubs first baseman Mark Grace and knuckleballer Tom Candiotti were the Diamondbacks primary color analysts for the 2006 and 2007 seasons.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] Former Diamondbacks third baseman Matt Williams also did color commentary on occasion, as did Cardinals and NBC broadcast legend Joe Garagiola, a longtime Phoenix-area resident and father of Joe Garagiola Jr., the first GM of the Diamondbacks.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The Diamondbacks announced in July 2007 that for the 2008 season, all regionally broadcast Diamondbacks TV games would be shown exclusively on Fox Sports Arizona (subsequently Bally Sports Arizona) and a few could possibly be shown on the national *MLB on Fox* telecasts.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] Bally Sports Arizona is seen in 2.8 million households in Arizona and New Mexico.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The previous flagship station since the inaugural 1998 season was KTVK (Channel 3), a popular over-the-air independent station (and former longtime ABC affiliate) in Phoenix.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] From 2009 to 2012, Grace and Sutton were tagged as the main broadcasters of the Diamondbacks with pre-game and postgame shows on Fox Sports Arizona, being hosted by Joe Borowski.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] On June 21, 2012, Sutton was suspended indefinitely amid rumors of insubordination.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] On August 24, the team announced that Grace had requested an indefinite leave of absence after being arrested for his second DUI in less than two years.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] Grace was later indicted on four DUI counts.) For the remainder of the 2012 season, Sutton was replaced by Greg Schulte (Jeff Munn replaced Schulte on the radio broadcast) and Grace was replaced by Luis Gonzalez.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] At the end of the 2012 season, the team announced that neither Sutton nor Grace would return for the 2013 season.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] On October 18, 2012, the team announced that Bob Brenly would return as a broadcaster to replace Grace and that he would be joined by then-ESPN personality Steve Berthiaume.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The English language flagship radio station is KTAR.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] Greg Schulte was the regular radio play-by-play voice, a 25-year veteran of sports radio in the Phoenix market, also well known for his previous work on Phoenix Suns, Arizona Cardinals, and Arizona State University (ASU) broadcasts.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] It was announced in February 2023 that he would be retiring after the 2023 MLB season.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] He would call games with analyst Tom Candiotti.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] Jeff Munn served as a backup radio play-by-play announcer until 2016; he served as the regular public address announcer at Chase Field in the early days of the franchise.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] He previously served as the public address announcer for the Suns in the 1990s at what became Footprint Center.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] He is also the play-by-play radio voice for ASU women's basketball.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] Mike Ferrin served in the same role for six years before parting ways with the team, and he was replaced by Chris Garagiola in December 2021.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The flagship Spanish language radio station is KHOV-FM 105.1 with Oscar Soria, Rodrigo López, and Richard Saenz.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] Games were televised in Spanish on KPHE-LP with Oscar Soria and Jerry Romo as the announcers, but this arrangement ended prior to the 2009 season due to the team switching fully to Fox Sports Arizona and the lack of carriage of KPHE-LP on the Cox cable system.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] All stats are as of February 8, 2025, from the Arizona Diamondbacks website.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The rivalry between the Diamondbacks and the Los Angeles Dodgers has been one of the fiercest divisional matchups for several years.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] Animosity between the two teams began to escalate during the 2010s in multiple incidents involving either team throwing pitches at one another or instigating into large-scale brawls between both benches.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] After eliminating the Diamondbacks and clinching the division on September 19, 2013, multiple Dodgers players celebrated the win by jumping into the pool at Chase Field.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The two sides met during the 2017 National League Division Series as the Diamondbacks were swept 3–0 by the Dodgers en route to their appearance in the World Series that season.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The Dodgers led the series 257–191 with a 3–0 lead in the postseason.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] After clinching the 2023 NL Wild Card berth and defeating the Milwaukee Brewers in the National League Wild Card Series, the Diamondbacks played the Dodgers again in the 2023 NLDS.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] There, the Diamondbacks emphatically swept the Dodgers to even the all-time postseason record between the two clubs at 3–3.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The Diamondbacks developed an on-and-off rivalry with the Colorado Rockies, often attributed to both teams being the newest in the division.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] Colorado had joined the NL West in 1993, while the Diamondbacks are the newest team in the league, joining in 1998.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The two teams have met twice in the postseason; notably during the 2007 National League Championship Series, which saw the Rockies enter the postseason as a wild card and go on to upset the division champion Diamondbacks in a sweep en route to the franchise's lone World Series appearance.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The two teams met again in the 2017 National League Wild Card Game, which Arizona won.
[src:coach-baseball/arizona-diamondbacks] The Arizona Diamondbacks farm system consists of seven minor league affiliates.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] Latham stole 129 bases during the 1887 season.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] His career total of 742 ranks seventh all-time in the majors.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] As a player-coach for the 1909 Giants, Latham, at age 49, became the oldest MLB player to steal a base.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] After his retirement as a player, he became what is acknowledged as the first full-time base coach in baseball history.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] For years he served as a coach and manager in the minor leagues.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] After retiring from baseball, Latham traveled to Great Britain, where he organized baseball matches for soldiers during World War I and taught baseball to the British.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] He later worked in baseball as a press box attendant.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] Latham's father was a bugler in the Union Army during the American Civil War.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] Latham became interested in baseball when soldiers returning from the battlefield brought the game of baseball with them.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] At the age of fourteen, he played with a local team from Stoneham, Massachusetts, as their catcher, fielding barehanded.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] In 1877, he played for a team in Pittsfield, Massachusetts, as a third baseman.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] Latham made his professional baseball debut with Springfield of the National Association in 1879.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] Latham made his major-league debut with the Buffalo Bisons of the National League (NL) in 1880; he is considered the first man from New Hampshire to play in MLB.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] He played for the Philadelphia Athletics of the Eastern Championship Association in 1881, and the Philadelphia Phillies of the League Alliance in 1882.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] Latham returned to the major leagues with the St.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] Louis Browns of the American Association (AA) in 1883.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] Latham was known as an excellent base stealer in his day.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] He led the AA in runs scored (152) during the 1886 season, batted .316, and stole 142 bases, plus another 12 stolen bases in the playoffs.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] In 1887, as a member of the Browns, he stole 129 bases.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] This record is not recognized by Major League Baseball, as stolen bases were defined differently prior to 1898.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] He led the league in stolen bases with 109 during the 1888 season.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] In 1890, he jumped to the Chicago Pirates of the Players' League.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] He returned to the NL with the Cincinnati Reds in July 1890 to serve as a utility player and coach.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] He played for Cincinnati through 1895, and was traded to the Browns after the 1895 season with Ed McFarland, Morgan Murphy, Tom Parrott and cash for Red Ehret and Heinie Peitz.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] The Browns released Latham after the 1896 season.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] Latham then returned to the minor leagues.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] He played for the Columbus Buckeyes/Senators of the Western League and Scranton Miners of the Eastern League in 1896.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] He played for the Mansfield Haymakers of the Interstate League in 1897.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] In 1898, he applied to become a NL umpire; instead, he played for the New Britain Rangers of the Connecticut State League and Hartford Cooperatives of the Atlantic League in 1898.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] Latham returned to the major leagues with the Washington Senators in 1899.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] He played for the Denver Grizzlies of the Western League in 1902.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] He made a handful of cameo appearances as a player for the New York Giants of the NL in 1909, becoming the oldest man in Major League history to steal a base, at the age of 49, a record that still stands today.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] Latham ended his career with 742 stolen bases.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] Latham's baserunning expertise was apparently purely instinctive.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] He holds the career record for errors at third base, with 822, more than 200 more than the next player on the list.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] Latham's arm had been injured in a throwing contest with a teammate, which led to Latham making weak or half-hearted attempts to field ground balls.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] Latham became an umpire in 1903 in the International League.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] In 1906, Latham managed the Jacksonville Jays of the Southern League.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] He also served as an umpire for the league and the South Atlantic League.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] Latham was Major League Baseball's first full-time coach.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] During his playing days, he would stand on the third base line and yell insults at the other team's pitcher, attempting to distract him and give the Browns an advantage.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] One of his techniques was to scream while running up and down the third base line during the pitcher's delivery.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] The coach's box was introduced to prevent him from doing this.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] While Cy Seymour coached third base for the Giants during a game against the Philadelphia Phillies, Seymour tackled Moose McCormick as he rounded third base and headed for home plate.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] When Giants manager John McGraw asked why, Seymour made an excuse about having the sun in his eyes.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] This led McGraw, realizing the need for a full-time coach, to hire Latham for the role, the first full-time coach in MLB.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] Latham tried to do the same things in New York as he had done years earlier in St.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] Louis, but times had changed and screaming obscenities was not looked well upon, as baseball was being changed into more of a family-friendly game by then.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] In the opinion of Giants player Fred Snodgrass, however, he was "probably the worst third base coach that ever lived".
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] After the 1910 season, Latham was let go by the Giants.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] In 1914, Latham coached with the Lynn Fighters of the New England League; in July 1914, he resigned from the team.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] Latham announced his retirement from professional baseball in 1915.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] He wrote for The Pittsburgh Press in 1915.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] Latham lived in England during World War I, where he organized baseball for the soldiers, and taught King George V about baseball.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] He returned to the United States in 1923, and opened a delicatessen on Saint Nicholas Avenue in Manhattan.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] He also served as a press box attendant for the Giants at the Polo Grounds and New York Yankees at Yankee Stadium.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] Known for his on-field antics, Latham was considered one of the funniest personalities in baseball.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] Nicknamed "The Freshest Man on Earth", Latham was a colorful player known for playing practical jokes, including on Browns owner Chris von der Ahe and manager Charles Comiskey.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] In one famous stunt, he lit a firecracker under third base in an effort to "wake himself up", after Comiskey had been complaining about him falling asleep on the job.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] Also he would occasionally put on a clown's nose while walking behind von der Ahe.
[src:coach-baseball/arlie-latham] A practical joke Latham pulled on Cy Seymour in March 1909 caused a fight between the two at the team's hotel, prompting McGraw to discharge Seymour from the team and seek a buyer.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] In baseball, a number of **coaches** assist in the smooth functioning of a team.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] They are assistants to the manager, who determines the starting lineup and batting order, decides how to substitute players during the game, and makes strategy decisions.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] Beyond the manager, more than a half dozen coaches may assist the manager in running the team.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] Essentially, baseball coaches are analogous to assistant coaches in other sports, as the baseball manager is to the head coach.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] Baseball is unique in that the manager and coaches typically all wear numbered uniforms similar to those of the players, due to the early practice of managers frequently being selected from the player roster.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] After the widespread adoption of numbered uniforms in the early 1930s, Joe McCarthy, another Hall of Fame manager, wore a full uniform but no number on his back for the remainder of his career with the New York Yankees, then the Boston Red Sox.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] All three men retired during or after the 1950 season.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] Full-time coaches in professional baseball date to 1909, when John McGraw of the New York Giants engaged Arlie Latham and Wilbert Robinson as coaches.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] By the 1920s, most major league teams had two full-time coaches stationed in foul territory near first base and third base when their team was batting, although the manager often doubled as third-base coach, and specialists such as pitching coaches were rare.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] After World War II, most major league teams listed between three and five coaches on their roster, as managers increasingly ran their teams from the dugout full-time, and appointed pitching and bullpen coaches to assist them and the baseline coaches.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] Batting and bench coaches came into vogue during the 1960s and later.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] Because of the proliferation of uniformed coaches in the modern game, by the late 2000s Major League Baseball had restricted the number of uniformed staff to six coaches and one manager during the course of a game.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] Beginning with the 2013 season, clubs have been permitted to employ a seventh uniformed coach, designated the assistant hitting coach, at their own discretion.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] The first bench coach in baseball was George Huff, who took that helm for the Illinois Fighting Illini baseball in 1905; at the time, it meant a coach present throughout the season.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] More recently, the bench coach is a team's second-in-command.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] The bench coach serves as an in-game advisor to the manager, offering situational advice and exchanging ideas to assist the manager in making strategy decisions, along with relaying scouting information from the front office to the players.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] If the manager is ejected, suspended, or unable to attend a game for any reason, the bench coach assumes the position of acting manager.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] If the manager is fired or resigns during the season, the bench coach is usually who is promoted to interim manager.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] The bench coach's responsibilities also include helping to set up the day's practice and stretching routines before a game, as well as coordinating spring training routines and practices.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] A **pitching coach** mentors and trains teams' pitchers.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] Pitching coaches can alter a pitcher's arm angle, placement on the pitching rubber, or pitch selection to improve the player's performance.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] The coach advises the manager on the condition of pitchers and their arms and serves as an in-game coach for the pitcher currently on the mound.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] When a manager makes a visit to the mound, he typically is doing so to make a pitching change or to discuss situational defense.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] A pitching coach also helps pitchers with their mechanics and pitch selection against specific batters who may be coming up.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] However, to talk about mechanics or how to pitch to a particular batter, the pitching coach is the one who typically visits the mound.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] The pitching coach is generally a former pitcher.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] One exception is Dave Duncan, the former pitching coach of the St.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] Prior to the early 1950s, pitching coaches were usually former catchers.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] The bullpen coach is similar to a pitching coach, but works primarily with relief pitchers in the bullpen.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] Bullpen coaches do not make mound visits; rather, they stay in the bullpen the entire game, working with relievers who are warming up to enter the game, while also offering advice on pitching mechanics and pitch selection.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] Generally, the bullpen coach is either a former pitcher or catcher.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] A **hitting coach**, as the name suggests, works with a team's players to improve their batting techniques and form.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] They monitor players' swings during the game and over the course of the season, advising them when necessary between at bats on adjustments to make.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] They also oversee batters' performance during practices, cage sessions, and pregame batting practice.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] With the advent of technology, hitting coaches are increasingly using video to analyze their hitters along with scouting the opposing pitchers.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] Video has allowed hitting coaches to clearly illustrate problem areas in the swing, making the adjustment period quicker for the player being analyzed.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] This process is typically called video analysis.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] Two on-field coaches are present when the team is batting.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] Stationed in designated coaches' boxes in foul territory near first and third base are the first base coach and third base coach.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] They assist in the direction of baserunners, help prevent pickoffs, and relay signals sent from the manager in the dugout to runners and batters.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] While the first base coach is primarily responsible for the batter as to whether he stops at first base or not, or for a runner already on first, the third base coach carries more responsibility.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] The bench coach, third base coach, and first base coach often are assigned additional responsibility for assisting players in specific areas, particularly defense.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] Common designations include outfield instructor, infield instructor, catching instructor, and baserunning instructor.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] When a coaching staff is assembled, the selection of the first base coach is frequently made with the purpose of filling a gap in these coaching responsibilities, as the actual in-game duties of a first base coach are relatively light.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] Teams may also employ individuals to work with players in other areas or activities.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] These positions sometimes include the word "coach" in their titles.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] Individuals holding these positions usually do not dress in uniform during games, as the number of uniformed coaches is restricted by Major League Baseball rules.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] The most prominent of these positions are the athletic trainer and the strength and conditioning coach.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] All Major League Baseball teams employ an athletic trainer; most employ a strength and conditioning coach.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] Other positions include bullpen catcher and batting practice pitcher.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] Some teams also employ additional coaches without specific responsibilities.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] Major League Baseball teams will have one or more person specifically assigned to each coaching position described above.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] However, minor league and amateur teams typically have coaches fulfill multiple responsibilities.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] A typical minor league/amateur team coaching structure will have a manager, a pitching coach, and a hitting coach, each of whom also assumes the responsibilities of the first and third base coaches, bullpen coach, etc.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] In college baseball in the U.S., the title "manager" is not used; the person who fills the role of a professional manager is instead called the "head coach".
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] Responsibilities of a youth baseball coach include providing a safe environment for everyone.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] A coach is responsible for inspecting fields and equipment that is used for practice and competition to ensure it is safe.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] Communication is key when dealing with youth baseball, as being positive to other coaching staff, umpires, administrators, and others shows that they have the players' best interests at heart.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] Coaches are there not to just work with the stars to get them better, but everyone so playing is a learning experience.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] Teaching the fundamental skills of baseball is important as a youth coach because in the end, baseball is a game, therefore coaches want players to have fun.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] Having a fun but productive practice environment is important.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] The rules of baseball are necessary in youth baseball.
[src:coach-baseball/coach-baseball] Many rules such as sliding, the strike zone, and defensive rules are needed.
